{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2018}} {{Use Indian English|date=October 2018}} {{Infobox writer <!--For more information, see [[:Template:Infobox Writer/doc]].--> | name = Gani Dahiwala | image = AbdulganiDahiwalaPic.jpg | image_size = | caption = | pseudonym = Gani Dahiwala | birth_name = Abdulgani Abdulkarim Dahiwala | birth_date = {{birth date|df=yes|1908|8|17}} | birth_place = [[Surat]], [[Gujarat]] | death_date = {{death date and age|df=yes|1987|3|5|1908|8|17}} | death_place = | resting_place = | occupation = poet, playwright | language = [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]] | nationality = Indian | education = Std. 3 | period = | genres = [[Ghazal]], [[Geet (song)|Geet]], Muktak | subjects = | movement = | notableworks = * ''Gatan Jharana'' (1953) * ''Ganimat'' (1971) | spouse = | children = | relatives = | awards = | signature = Gani Dahiwala autograph.svg | signature_alt = | years_active = 1942 - 1987 | website = }}
'''Abdulgani Abdulkarim Dahiwala, '''popularly known as '''Gani Dahiwala''' was a [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]] poet.
==Life== Abdulgani Dahiwala was born on 17 August 1908 at [[Surat]]. He came to [[Ahmedabad]] in 1928 but later returned to Surat in 1930 when he started a tailor shop. He established the music group ''Swarsangam'' in Surat. Later he was a founding member of Mahagujarat Gazal Mandal in 1942. He wrote satirical poetry in the ''Gujarat Mitra'' daily published from Surat. He traveled to Pakistan in 1981 under Cultural Exchange Scheme set by Government of India. He died on 5 March 1987.<ref name="GSP">{{cite web | title=સવિશેષ પરિચય: ગની દહીંવાલા | website=[[Gujarati Sahitya Parishad]] | url=http://gujaratisahityaparishad.com/prakashan/sarjako/savishesh/Savishesh-Gani-Dahiwala.html | language=gu | accessdate=9 September 2015}}</ref><ref name="Datta1987">{{cite book|author=Amaresh Datta|title=Encyclopaedia of Indian Literature: A-Devo|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ObFCT5_taSgC&pg=PA832|year=1987|publisher=Sahitya Akademi|isbn=978-81-260-1803-1|page=832}}</ref>
==Works== ''Gata Zarana'' (1953), ''Mahek'' (1961), ''Madhurap'' (1971), ''Ganimat'' (1971) and ''Nirant ''(1981) are collections of different genres of poetry such as songs, [[ghazal]], ''Muktaka'' (single stanza poetry). ''Jashne Shahadat'' (1957) is Hindi musical play based on [[Indian Rebellion of 1857]]. ''Pehle Maale'' is his three act play staged in 1959-60 but never published.<ref name="GSP"/><ref name="Datta1988">{{cite book|author=Amaresh Datta|title=Encyclopaedia of Indian Literature|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zB4n3MVozbUC&pg=PA1390|year=1988|publisher=Sahitya Akademi|isbn=978-81-260-1194-0|page=1390}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Poet|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=o-1HAAAAMAAJ|year=1974|publisher=K. Srinivas|page=134}}</ref><ref name="Publicity1958">{{cite book|author=Bombay (India : State). Directorate of Publicity|title=What Bombay Government Did and Said|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=118dAAAAIAAJ|date=October 1958|page=2}}</ref> All of his poems have published as ''Hoy Na Hoy Vyakti Ne Enu Naam Bolaya Kare'', compiled by [[Bhagvatikumar Sharma]] and Ravindra Parekh, in 2009.<ref>{{cite magazine |date= March 2016 |magazine= [[Gazalvishwa]] |editor1-last= Vyas |editor1-first= Rajesh |location= [[Ahmedabad]] |publisher= Vali Gujarati Gazalkendra }} To</ref>
