{{Infobox writer | name = Ahmad Tafazzoli | image = | imagesize = | alt = | caption = | pseudonym = | birth_name = | birth_date = 16 December 1937 | birth_place = [[Isfahan]] | occupation = [[Writer]], [[Iranologist]] | nationality = [[Iran]]ian | ethnicity = | citizenship = | education = | alma_mater = | period = | genre = | subject = | movement = | notableworks = | spouse = | partner = | children = | relatives = | influences = | influenced = | awards = | signature = | website = | portaldisp = }} '''Ahmad Tafazzoli''' (16 December 1937, [[Isfahan]] – January 15, 1997, [[Tehran]]) ({{lang-fa|احمد تفضلی}}) was a prominent [[Iranian peoples|Iranian]] [[Iranology|Iranist]] and master of ancient Iranian literature and culture. Tafazzoli was a faculty member of [[Tehran University]].
One of his most important books and his latest masterpiece is "Pre-Islamic Persian Literature". [[Jaleh Amouzegar]] contributed in editing it.
In January 1997, Ahmad Tafazzoli was found dead in [[Punak]], a suburb northwest of Tehran. He was known to have contacts with Iranian academics working abroad, and many of his colleagues believed that the authorities were behind his death, as part of the [[chain murders of Iran]]. While the precise circumstances remained unclear, Tafazzoli's death created a [[climate of fear]] at the university and discouraged criticism of the government.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/worldreport/Mideast-04.htm|title=Human Rights Watch World Report 1998|publisher=[[Human Rights Watch]]|accessdate=2007-10-09|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929090443/http://www.hrw.org/worldreport/Mideast-04.htm|archivedate=2007-09-29}}</ref>
