'''Ihor Pavlyuk''' (sometimes spelled as Ihor Pawlyuk, Igor Pavlyk, Igor Pavluk; [[Ukrainian language|Ukrainian]]: [[:uk:Павлюк Ігор Зиновійович|І́гор Зино́війович Павлю́к]], [[Russian language|Russian]]: [[:ru:Павлюк, Игорь Зиновьевич|Игорь Зиновьевич Павлюк]], born 1 January 1967 in [[Rozhysche Raion|Uzhova]], [[Ukrainian SSR]]) is a [[Ukrainians|Ukrainian]] writer, translator and research worker.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://wnu-ukraine.com/about-ukraine/culture/108/|title = Modern Ukrainian Literature|date = October 16, 2011|accessdate = July 26, 2015|website = wnu-ukraine.com|publisher = World News Ukraine|last = |first = }}</ref>

He is a Winner of a 2013 [[English PEN]] Award<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://ewordnews.com/literary-news/2013/11/19/here-are-the-winners-of-the-2013-english-pen-awards|title = Here Are The Winners Of The 2013 English PEN Awards|date = 2013|accessdate = July 26, 2015|website = ewordnews.com|publisher = eWorldNews|last = |first = }}</ref><ref name="om">{{Cite web|url = http://worldbookshelf.englishpen.org/Writers-in-Translation-books-authors-Ihor-Pavlyuk|title = Ihor Pavlyuk|date = July 24, 2014|accessdate = July 26, 2015|website =worldbookshelf.englishpen.org/|publisher = English PEN's World Bookshelf|last = |first = }}</ref> and a Doctor of Social Communication.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://aspirant.kiev.ua/tex/prisudjeno-naukoviy-stupin-doktora-nauk.html|title = Присуджено науковий ступінь доктора наук|date = 2010|accessdate = July 26, 2015|website = aspirant.kiev.ua|publisher = Aspirant Ukraine|last = |first = }}</ref>

Ihor Pavlyuk is a member of the European Society of Authors.

==Life and career==
Ihor Pavlyuk was born in the [[Volyn]] region on January 1, 1967. His mother died in ten days after giving birth to him. He was raised at home of his grandfather and grandmother on his mother's side — migrants with [[Chełm|Helm]] region.

He studied at the [[Saint Petersburg]] [[military engineering-technical university]], which he left in order to pursue his career as a writer. He was, as a result, sentenced to a period of hard labour in the Taiga ([[Zabaykalye|Zabaykal'skiy region]]) but continued to write as best he could, driven by a nostalgia for his [[Ukraine|Ukrainian]] homeland, until he was liberated by the fall of the [[Soviet Union]].<ref name="om" />

In 1992 Ihor Pavlyuk graduated from the Department of Journalism at [[Lviv University]] and worked as the correspondent of religious [[News media|press]] and [[radio]] in [[Lviv]].

He has participated in various international literary festivals, including [[Estonia]], [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]], [[Russia]], [[Belarus]], [[Germany]], [[Italy]], the [[United States of America]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ukrainiantours.com/images/Ukrainian_Ihor_Pavlyuk_presents_his_poetry_in_Florida_June_28-027.doc |title=Ukrainian Ihor Pavlyuk presents his poetry in Florida! |date=June 28, 2014 |accessdate=July 28, 2015 |website=ukrainiantours.com |publisher=Ukrainian tours |last= |first= |deadurl=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129053632/http://www.ukrainiantours.com/images/Ukrainian_Ihor_Pavlyuk_presents_his_poetry_in_Florida_June_28-027.doc |archivedate=November 29, 2014 |df= }}</ref> [[Poland]], [[Turkey]], [[Ireland]], [[Pakistan]],<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.dawn.com/news/1075857/two-day-intl-peace-conference-kicks-off|title = Two-day Int’l Peace Conference kicks off|date = December 23, 2013|accessdate = July 26, 2015|website = dawn.com|publisher = DAWN|last = |first = }}</ref> [[England]],<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.englishpen.org/event/ukrainian-poetry-evening/|title = Ukrainian Poetry Evening|date = March 6, 2014|accessdate = July 26, 2015|website = englishpen.org|publisher = English PEN|last = |first = }}</ref> [[Czech Republic]] and international editions about Ukrainians from [[Volyn]] region, Ukrainian writers and poets.{{citation needed|date=February 2016}}

Now Ihor Pavlyuk is Leading Researcher of [[Taras Shevchenko]] Institute of Literature of the National Academy of Sciences of Ukraine in [[Kiev]],<ref>[http://www.ilnan.gov.ua/XX_st.htm Відділ української літератури ХХ ст.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150916170120/http://www.ilnan.gov.ua/XX_st.htm |date=2015-09-16 }}</ref> professor of Ukrainian media [[Ivan Franko National University of Lviv]], a member of the editorial boards of literary, art and scientific magazines: "Золота пектораль",<ref>[http://zolotapektoral.te.ua/redaktsijna-kolehiya. Золота пектораль. Редколегія]</ref> "Дзвін",<ref>[http://dzvinua.blogspot.in/p/blog-page.html Дзвін. Редколегія]</ref> "Українська літературна газета",<ref>[http://litgazeta.com.ua/pro-gazetu/ Українська літературна газета. Редколегія]</ref> "Вісник [[Ivan Franko National University of Lviv|Львівського університету"]].<ref>[http://lnu.edu.ua/faculty/jur/visnyk-journ.htm Вісник Львівського університету. Редколегія] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150508225301/http://lnu.edu.ua/faculty/jur/visnyk-journ.htm |date=2015-05-08 }}</ref>

Works of Ihor Pavlyuk have been translated into [[Russian language|Russian]], [[Belarusian language|Belarusian]], [[Polish language|Polish]], [[English language|English]], [[French language|French]], [[Latvian language|Latvian]], [[Bulgarian language|Bulgarian]], [[Japanese language|Japanese]] and other languages and published in such magazines as "The Apple Valley Review" (Volume 7, Number 2 (Fall 2012),<ref>[http://www.applevalleyreview.com/ HORSES IN MASKS]</ref> "Muddy River Poetry Review",<ref>[http://www.muddyriverpoetryreview.com/Spring%202013/Steve%20Komarnyckyj.pdf Two Poems by Ihor Pavlyuk, translated from the Ukrainian by Steve Komarnyckyj]</ref> ''[[Asymptote (journal)|Asymptote]]'',<ref>[http://asymptotejournal.com/article.php?cat=Poetry&id=142&curr_index=9&curPage=current Mussel]</ref> "Gold Dust" (Issue 23),<ref>[http://www.golddustmagazine.co.uk/BackIssues/iss23_gene.htm A Flight Over the Black Sea. Istanbul. The Return]</ref> "The Adirondack Review",<ref>[http://www.theadirondackreview.com/ihorpavlyuk.html Two Poems]</ref> "The Recusant",<ref>[http://www.therecusant.org.uk/#/ihor-pavlyuk-poems/4584041067 The Old Water Flows]</ref><ref>[http://www.therecusant.org.uk/#/ihor-pavlyuk-poems-3/4584041224 From Polissya]</ref> "Metamorphoses",<ref>[http://www.smith.edu/metamorphoses/issues/2015spring.html The Bread of Childhood]</ref> "Eurasia Review",<ref>[http://www.eurasiareview.com/21102016-a-warriors-white-dance-of-words-oped/ A Warrior’s White Dance Of Words – OpEd]</ref> "The world poets quarterly",<ref>[http://blog.sina.com.cn/s/blog_5f697e440102x8co.html Good Dog (and another poem)]</ref> and many others.

Ihor Pavlyuk is the protagonist of the film "Between Bug and God"<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6s0-5iL_YCw Ihor Pavlyuk: "Between Bug and God"]</ref> and film "Voice".<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6A6XI2hVYsw Film about Ukrainian poet Ihor Pavlyuk]</ref>

American actors read poems by Ihor Pavlyuk.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8s0NUVsuO_I American actors read poems by Ihor Pavlyuk]</ref>

The book of Ihor Pavlyuk "A Flight over the Black Sea" became the winning book within Writers in Translation competition by [[English PEN]] club.<ref>[http://112.international/society/poetry-of-ukrainian-author-became-book-of-the-year-in-the-united-kingdom-1446.html Poetry of Ukrainian author became book of the year in the United Kingdom]</ref><ref>[http://worldbookshelf.englishpen.org/vote_results The best of the World Bookshelf]</ref>

Ihor Pavlyuk is married.
His wife Lyudmyla Pavlyuk is Associate Professor at Department of Journalism, [[Lviv University]].
Daughters Nadiya and Olesya are students.

