{{Infobox language |name=Rusenu |region=eastern [[East Timor]] |extinct=Unknown, likely 20th century |familycolor=Papuan |fam1=[[Trans–New Guinea]] |fam2=[[West Bomberai languages|West Bomberai]] |fam3=[[Timor–Alor–Pantar languages|Timor–Alor–Pantar]] |fam4=[[Eastern Timor languages|Eastern Timor]] |fam5=[[Fataluku language|Fataluku]] ? |iso3=none |glotto=none }}
'''Rusenu''' is a virtually extinct [[Papuan languages|Papuan language]] discovered in 2007. It was spoken in the east of what is now [[East Timor]].
Rusenu was discovered accidentally by the Dutch-Timorese linguist [[Aone van Engelenhoven]], who was studying a language called [[Makuva]], thought since the 1950s to be extinct,<ref name="raadsel">{{cite web | last = van Wayenburg | first = Bruno | authorlink = | coauthors = | title = Raadselachtig Rusenu: Taalkundige ontdekt taalgeheimen en geheimtalen op Oost-Timor | work = | publisher = [[VPRO]] Noorderlicht | date = 2007-04-04 | url = http://noorderlicht.vpro.nl/artikelen/34024406/ | format = | doi = | accessdate = 2009-03-11}}</ref>. Just as he was about to leave for the Netherlands, he was informed about the existence of a language called Rusenu. There was said to be only one elderly woman "who had some knowledge of it."<ref name="hoop">{{cite web | last = van Wayenburg | first = Bruno | authorlink = | coauthors = | title = Sprankje hoop voor talenvorsers: Nieuw ontdekte taal Rusenu alweer bijna uitgestorven | work = | publisher = [[VPRO]] Noorderlicht | date = 2007-09-13 | url = http://noorderlicht.vpro.nl/artikelen/36635727/ | format = | doi = | accessdate = 2009-03-11}} </ref> He gave his tape recorder to his informant, who subsequently interrogated the women and her son. She remembered a nursery rhyme, which she was unable to interpret (as was her entire tribe). Her son could count to ten in the language. After Van Engelenhoven analysed and transcribed the recording, he concluded that Rusenu, "albeit remotely related to [[Fataluku language|Fataluku]], is a separate language."<ref name="hoop"/> The speakers of Rusenu were also claimed to have been responsible for the several thousand years old [[rock drawing]]s on East Timor,<ref name="raadsel"/> in the [[Ile Kére Kére caves]].<ref>{{cite web | last = Hagers | first = Steven | authorlink = | coauthors = | title = Een vergeten taal op Oost-Timor | work = | publisher = Kennislink | date = 2007-03-20 | url = http://www.kennislink.nl/web/show?id=166505 | format = | doi = | accessdate = 2009-03-11}}</ref>
Van Engelenhoven reports this discovery triggered rumors about other languages that have survived to date as cants, and hopes to discover some more unknown East Timorese languages in the near future.<ref name="hoop"/>
Ruseno is one of the cultural group names in the eastern part of Timor-Leste. Etymologically, Rus-En-O in Fataluku dialect means window and door.{{cn|date=January 2016}}
